<p>After some delays due to the line fire in San Bernardino, we were finally able to test the changes. For <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> values, we tested them for hours before, and eventually showed that 0,0,0 were the best values, but we are still unsure of this. Even a value of 0.1 would cause a greater error than a value of 0. Attached below is one video of 0,0,0 values and another of 5,0,0 values.</p>
<p>Also, we have some more details on the problem. The Robot was not going straight forward after the first path, and was actually following the second path. However the robot severely underestimated its location, and to account for the error drives forward to begin the next path. Do you have any advice for this?</p>
<p>As for the rest of the changes, could you provide some more clarification for DriveStation.getHeading? We are a little confused by this change, and we don’t know exactly where to implement it.</p>
<p>Thanks so much for your help!<br>
We definitely saw an improvement overall.</p>
<p>Videos: <a href="https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1dyRYBOcG5_ZzySUy4wqELfFYmvBunscy?usp=drive_link" class="inline-onebox" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">RedlandsRoboticsTest - Google Drive</a></p>","post_number":13,"post_type":1,"posts_count":20,"updated_at":"2024-09-13T18:02:58.951Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":12,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":80,"readers_count":79,"score":16.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":470263,"topic_slug":"pathplanner-following-multiple-paths-does-not-work","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1dyRYBOcG5_ZzySUy4wqELfFYmvBunscy?usp=drive_link","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"RedlandsRoboticsTest - Google Drive","clicks":3}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":38743,"username":"bovlb","name":"Gavin Matthews","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/bovlb/{size}/167232_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":63609,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"crazyface"},"post_url":"/t/pathplanner-following-multiple-paths-does-not-work/470263/13","custom_user_title":"crazyface","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3423410,"name":"Gavin Matthews","username":"bovlb","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/bovlb/{size}/167232_2.png","created_at":"2024-09-13T19:00:48.851Z","cooked":"<p>It’s hard to see, but from what I can make out in the video, the field position determined from the odometry does not correspond to how the robot is moving.  You need to sort that out, say using teleop, before you have any chance of getting auto paths or <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> controllers to work.</p>
<p>In the constructor for <code>SwerveModule</code>, I recommend you call <code>restoreFactoryDefaults</code> on each motor at the start, and then call <code>burnFlash</code> on each motor at the end.  This means that you’re not inheriting any configuration from other code or previous uses of the controller, and you won’t lose configuration in the event of momentary power loss to the controller.</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">    drivePidController = new PIDController(0.75,1.5, 0);
</code></pre>
<p>Where did you get these values from?  They seem a bit high.</p>
<p>My point about <code>getHeading</code> was a fairly minor one.  I was suggesting that instead of:</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">    public double getHeading() {
        return -Math.IEEEremainder(gyro.getAngle(), 360);
    }

    public Rotation2d getRotation2d() {
        return Rotation2d.fromDegrees(getHeading());
    }

...
  odometer.resetPosition(
    Rotation2d.fromDegrees(getHeading())
</code></pre>
<p>your code would be tidier if you had:</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">    public Rotation2d getRotation2d() {
        return gyro.getRotation2d();
    }

...

  odometer.resetPosition(
    getRotation2d()
</code></pre>
<p>In other words, just use <code>Rotation2d</code> throughout rather than continually converting in and out of degrees.  This will make your code less error-prone.</p>","post_number":14,"post_type":1,"posts_count":20,"updated_at":"2024-09-13T20:20:49.587Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":74,"readers_count":73,"score":29.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":470263,"topic_slug":"pathplanner-following-multiple-paths-does-not-work","display_username":"Gavin Matthews","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":38743,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Programming mentor, Team 2102, RI, CSA (he/him)"},"post_url":"/t/pathplanner-following-multiple-paths-does-not-work/470263/14","custom_user_title":"Programming mentor, Team 2102, RI, CSA (he/him)","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3423776,"name":"","username":"crazyface","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/c/67e7ee/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-09-14T22:24:48.057Z","cooked":"<p>Thank you for your changes, they were really helpful. With your changes we think we have the problem pinpointed. It seems the the Robot position is never changing. We have attached a video with the problem. We think the problem might be in periodic for swerveSubsystem, but aren’t completely sure. We went to all instances of resetOdometery 